message.content: A group $G$ is defined to be "sane" if every subgroup $N$ of it that is not the whole group (i.e., $N < G$) is cyclic.
A group \( G \) is called "sane" if every subgroup \( N \) of \( G \), except \( G \) itself, is cyclic.
A group \( G \) is called *sane* if every proper subgroup \( N \) of \( G \) is cyclic.
A group \( G \) is called "sane" if every subgroup \( N \) of \( G \) that is strictly less than the entire group is cyclic.
A group $G$ is called *sane* if every subgroup $N$ of $G$, other than the whole group, is cyclic.
The definition states that a group $G$ is considered *sane* if every subgroup $N$ of $G$ that is not the entire group (i.e., $N < \top$) is cyclic.
A group $G$ is called "sane" if every proper subgroup $N$ of $G$ is cyclic.
A group $G$ is called "sane" if for every subgroup $N$ of $G$, where $N$ is not the whole group, $N$ is cyclic.
